## 2. Core Principles (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

1. **Schema-First Design:** GraphQL schema is the contract. Write schema first, then implement resolvers.
2. **Nullability by Default:** Fields are nullable unless explicitly required with `!`.
3. **Explicit Error Types:** Use typed errors with error codes, not generic strings.
4. **Pagination for Collections:** All lists that can grow unbounded MUST use cursor-based pagination.
5. **Input Validation:** Validate all inputs at the resolver layer before calling service layer.
6. **Idempotency:** Mutations SHOULD be idempotent where possible (use idempotency keys).

Violating these principles produces inconsistent, error-prone APIs.

---

## 3. Schema Design Patterns

### 3.1 Naming Conventions (MANDATORY)

#### Types
- **Objects:** PascalCase, singular nouns: `User`, `Invitation`, `Event`
- **Enums:** PascalCase, singular nouns: `InvitationStatus`, `EventType`
- **Inputs:** PascalCase, suffix with `Input`: `CreateEventInput`, `UpdateUserInput`
- **Interfaces:** PascalCase, adjective or noun: `Node`, `Timestamped`, `Auditable`

#### Fields
- **Queries:** camelCase, descriptive: `user(id: ID!)`, `invitations(filter: InvitationFilter!)`
- **Mutations:** camelCase, verb + noun: `createEvent`, `updateInvitation`, `deleteUser`
- **Field names:** camelCase: `firstName`, `createdAt`, `invitationStatus`

#### Arguments
- **Required args:** Use `!` suffix: `user(id: ID!)`
- **Optional filters:** Use input objects: `invitations(filter: InvitationFilter, pagination: PaginationInput)`

**Examples:**

```graphql
# ✅ GOOD
type User {
  id: ID!
  firstName: String!
  lastName: String!
  email: String!
  createdAt: DateTime!
}

type Query {
  user(id: ID!): User
  users(filter: UserFilter, pagination: PaginationInput): UserConnection!
}

type Mutation {
  createUser(input: CreateUserInput!): CreateUserPayload!
  updateUser(id: ID!, input: UpdateUserInput!): UpdateUserPayload!
}

# ❌ BAD
type user {  # Wrong: lowercase type name
  ID: ID!  # Wrong: uppercase field name
  first_name: String!  # Wrong: snake_case
}

type Query {
  getUser(id: ID!): User  # Wrong: redundant "get" prefix
  UserList: [User]  # Wrong: PascalCase query name
}
```

---

### 3.2 Nullability Rules (CRITICAL)

**Default:** Fields are **nullable** unless you're certain they will ALWAYS exist.

**When to use non-null (`!`):**
- Primary keys: `id: ID!`
- Required business fields: `email: String!` (if email is mandatory)
- Guaranteed system fields: `createdAt: DateTime!`
- Non-null collections: `users: [User!]!` (list itself non-null, items non-null)

**When to use nullable:**
- Optional fields: `phoneNumber: String` (user may not provide)
- Relationships that may not exist: `organization: Organization` (user may not belong to one)
- Fields that may fail to load: `profileImage: String` (S3 URL may be unavailable)

**Critical Rule:**
> Making a field non-null is a **breaking change** if it was previously nullable. Always start nullable, make non-null later if needed.

**Examples:**

```graphql
# ✅ GOOD
type User {
  id: ID!                     # Always exists (primary key)
  email: String!              # Required by business rules
  firstName: String!          # Required by business rules
  lastName: String!           # Required by business rules
  phoneNumber: String         # Optional (user may not provide)
  profileImageUrl: String     # Optional (may not be uploaded)
  organization: Organization  # Optional (user may not belong to one)
  createdAt: DateTime!        # System field, always exists
}

# ❌ BAD
type User {
  id: ID                      # Wrong: primary key should be non-null
  email: String               # Wrong: email is required by business rules
  phoneNumber: String!        # Wrong: phone is optional, forcing non-null will break clients
  organization: Organization! # Wrong: not all users belong to an organization
}
```

---

### 3.3 Pagination (MANDATORY for unbounded lists)

**Pattern:** Cursor-based pagination (Relay-style Connections)

**When to paginate:**
- Any list that can grow unbounded: `invitations`, `events`, `users`
- Lists with >20 items expected

**When NOT to paginate:**
- Enums (fixed size)
- Small, bounded lists: `roles` (if there are only 3-5 roles)

**Schema Pattern:**

```graphql
# Connection type
type UserConnection {
  edges: [UserEdge!]!
  pageInfo: PageInfo!
  totalCount: Int!  # Optional: total count (expensive query, use sparingly)
}

type UserEdge {
  node: User!
  cursor: String!
}

type PageInfo {
  hasNextPage: Boolean!
  hasPreviousPage: Boolean!
  startCursor: String
  endCursor: String
}

# Input for pagination
input PaginationInput {
  first: Int   # Forward pagination: first N items after cursor
  after: String  # Cursor to start after
  last: Int    # Backward pagination: last N items before cursor
  before: String  # Cursor to start before
}

# Query
type Query {
  users(
    filter: UserFilter
    pagination: PaginationInput
  ): UserConnection!
}
```

**Cursor Encoding:**
- Cursors MUST be opaque strings (Base64-encoded, not exposed implementation details)
- Example cursor: `base64("User:123:2024-01-15T10:30:00Z")` (combines ID + timestamp for stable ordering)

**Default Pagination:**
- Default `first`: 20 items
- Max `first`: 100 items (reject requests with `first > 100`)

---

### 3.4 Input Objects (MANDATORY for mutations)

**Pattern:** Use Input objects for all mutation arguments, NOT individual scalar arguments.

**Why:** Easier to evolve, clearer intent, better validation grouping.

**Schema Pattern:**

```graphql
# ✅ GOOD: Input object
input CreateEventInput {
  title: String!
  description: String
  startTime: DateTime!
  endTime: DateTime!
  location: String
  maxAttendees: Int
}

type Mutation {
  createEvent(input: CreateEventInput!): CreateEventPayload!
}

# ❌ BAD: Individual arguments
type Mutation {
  createEvent(
    title: String!
    description: String
    startTime: DateTime!
    endTime: DateTime!
    location: String
    maxAttendees: Int
  ): Event!  # Also wrong: should return payload type, not entity directly
}
```

**Naming:**
- Input types: `{Action}{Entity}Input` → `CreateEventInput`, `UpdateUserInput`
- Payload types: `{Action}{Entity}Payload` → `CreateEventPayload`, `UpdateUserPayload`

---

### 3.5 Mutation Response Patterns (MANDATORY)

**Pattern:** Always return a **Payload type**, never return the entity directly.

**Why:**
- Allows returning errors alongside success data
- Extensible (can add metadata later)
- Supports partial success scenarios

**Schema Pattern:**

```graphql
# ✅ GOOD: Payload type
type CreateEventPayload {
  event: Event            # The created entity (nullable if creation failed)
  errors: [UserError!]    # Validation/business errors
  success: Boolean!       # Quick success check
}

type UserError {
  message: String!        # Human-readable error message
  field: String           # Field that caused error (for input validation)
  code: ErrorCode!        # Machine-readable error code
}

enum ErrorCode {
  VALIDATION_ERROR
  UNAUTHORIZED
  NOT_FOUND
  DUPLICATE_ENTRY
  BUSINESS_RULE_VIOLATION
}

type Mutation {
  createEvent(input: CreateEventInput!): CreateEventPayload!
}

# ❌ BAD: Return entity directly
type Mutation {
  createEvent(input: CreateEventInput!): Event!  # Cannot return validation errors
}
```

**Success Response Example:**
```json
{
  "data": {
    "createEvent": {
      "success": true,
      "event": { "id": "123", "title": "Birthday Party" },
      "errors": []
    }
  }
}
```

**Error Response Example:**
```json
{
  "data": {
    "createEvent": {
      "success": false,
      "event": null,
      "errors": [
        {
          "message": "Start time must be in the future",
          "field": "startTime",
          "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR"
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

---

### 3.6 Filtering Patterns (RECOMMENDED)

**Pattern:** Use Input objects for filters, group by entity.

```graphql
input UserFilter {
  search: String             # Full-text search across name/email
  status: UserStatus         # Enum filter
  createdAfter: DateTime     # Date range filter
  organizationId: ID         # Relationship filter
}

type Query {
  users(filter: UserFilter, pagination: PaginationInput): UserConnection!
}
```

**Filter Naming:**
- Boolean operations: `isActive: Boolean`, `hasOrganization: Boolean`
- Comparison: `createdAfter: DateTime`, `createdBefore: DateTime`
- Exact match: `status: UserStatus`, `organizationId: ID`
- Search: `search: String` (full-text across multiple fields)

---

### 3.7 Interfaces vs Unions (When to Use)

**Use Interface when:**
- Types share common fields
- You need to query shared fields without type fragments

**Example:**
```graphql
interface Node {
  id: ID!
}

interface Timestamped {
  createdAt: DateTime!
  updatedAt: DateTime!
}

type User implements Node & Timestamped {
  id: ID!
  createdAt: DateTime!
  updatedAt: DateTime!
  email: String!
}

type Event implements Node & Timestamped {
  id: ID!
  createdAt: DateTime!
  updatedAt: DateTime!
  title: String!
}

# Query
type Query {
  node(id: ID!): Node  # Polymorphic lookup
}
```

**Use Union when:**
- Types do NOT share common fields
- Representing multiple possible return types

**Example:**
```graphql
union SearchResult = User | Event | Organization

type Query {
  search(query: String!): [SearchResult!]!
}

# Client query
query {
  search(query: "birthday") {
    ... on User { id email }
    ... on Event { id title }
    ... on Organization { id name }
  }
}
```

